# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: franco-prussian-war
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] Division*) was a unit of the Prussian/German Army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It was formed as the 15th Division on September 5, 1818, in Koblenz from a troop brigade.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It became the 16th Division on December 14, 1818, and moved its headquarters to Trier.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The division was subordinated in peacetime to the VIII Army Corps (*VIII.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The division was disbanded in 1919 during the demobilization of the German Army after World War I.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It was mainly recruited in the densely populated Prussian Rhine Province, mainly along the Rhine and the cities and towns along the Moselle River.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The 16th Division fought in the Austro-Prussian War in 1866, seeing action in the Battle of Königgrätz.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] In the Franco-Prussian War of 1870-71, the division fought in the Battle of Spicheren, the Battle of Mars-la-Tour, the Battle of Gravelotte (also called the Battle of Gravelotte-St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] Privat) and the Siege of Metz, and then in the battles of Amiens, Hallue, and St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] During World War I, the division marched through Luxembourg, Belgium and France, in what became known to the Allies as the Great Retreat, culminating in the First Battle of the Marne.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] In 1916, it fought in the Battle of the Somme.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The division was briefly sent to the Eastern Front in late 1916.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It saw action in 1917 in the Battle of Passchendaele, also known as the Third Battle of Ypres.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It participated in the 1918 German spring offensive, including the Battle of the Lys, and defended against the Allied counteroffensives, including the Second Battle of the Somme.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The 16th Infantry Division was a highly regarded division early in the war, known as the Iron Division, but by 1918 Allied intelligence rated it a second class division.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] During wartime, the 16th Division, like other regular German divisions, was redesignated an infantry division.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] German divisions underwent various organizational changes after the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The 16th Division received a new infantry brigade, the 80th, in 1897.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] It lost the 32nd Infantry Brigade, whose recruiting area was outside the Rhineland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The 15th Division's 30th Infantry Brigade then went to the 16th Division in exchange for the 80th Infantry Brigade.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] On mobilization in August 1914 at the beginning of World War I, most divisional cavalry, including brigade headquarters, was withdrawn to form cavalry divisions or split up among divisions as reconnaissance units.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] Divisions received engineer companies and other support units from their higher headquarters.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] The 16th Division was again renamed the 16th Infantry Division.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] Divisions underwent many changes during the war, with regiments moving from division to division, and some being destroyed and rebuilt.
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] During the war, most divisions became triangular - one infantry brigade with three infantry regiments rather than two infantry brigades of two regiments (a "square division").
[src:franco-prussian-war/16th-division-german-empire] An artillery commander replaced the artillery brigade headquarters, the cavalry was further reduced, the engineer contingent was increased, and a divisional signals command was created.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The **coup d'état of 2 December 1851** was a self-coup staged by Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte (later Napoleon III), at the time President of France under the Second Republic.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Code-named **Operation Rubicon** and timed to coincide with the anniversary of his uncle Napoleon I's coronation and victory at Austerlitz, the coup dissolved the National Assembly, granted dictatorial powers to the president and preceded the establishment of the Second French Empire a year later.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Faced with the prospect of having to leave office in 1852, Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte (nephew of Napoleon Bonaparte) staged the coup in order to stay in power and implement his reform programs; these included the restoration of universal male suffrage previously abolished by the legislature.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The continuation of his authority and the power to produce a new constitution were approved days later by a constitutional referendum, resulting in the Constitution of 1852, which greatly increased the powers and the term length of the president.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] A year after the coup, Bonaparte proclaimed himself "Emperor of the French" under the regnal name Napoleon III.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] In 1848, Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte was elected President of France through universal male suffrage, taking 74% of the vote.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He did this with the support of the Party of Order after running against Louis Eugène Cavaignac.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Subsequently, he was in constant conflict with the members (*députés*) of the National Assembly.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Contrary to the Party's expectations that Louis-Napoleon would be easy to manipulate (Adolphe Thiers had called him a "cretin whom we will lead [by the nose]"), he proved himself an agile and cunning politician.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He succeeded in imposing his choices and decisions upon the Assembly, which had once again become conservative in the aftermath of the June Days uprising in 1848.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He broke away from the control of the Party of Order and created the *Ministère des Commis*, appointing General Hautpoul as its head, in 1849.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 3 January 1850, he dismissed Changarnier, a dissident in the Party of Order, thereby provoking an open conflict within the party.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He also actively encouraged the creation of numerous anti-parliament newspapers and acquired the support of 150 members of Parliament, the "Parti de l'Elysée".
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The provisions of the constitution that prohibited an incumbent president from seeking re-election appeared to force the end of Louis-Napoleon's rule in December 1852.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He therefore spent the first half of 1851 trying to force changes to the constitution through Parliament so he could be re-elected.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Bonaparte travelled through the provinces and organised petitions to rally popular support.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Two-thirds of the General Council supported Louis-Napoleon's cause, but in the Assembly, supporters of the Duke of Orléans, led by Thiers, concluded an alliance with the far left to oppose Louis-Napoleon's plans.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] In January 1851, the Parliament voted no confidence in the Ministère des Commis.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 19 July, it refused the constitutional reform proposed by Louis-Napoleon, also scrapping universal male suffrage in an effort to break popular support for Bonaparte.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The coup d'état was meticulously planned from 20 August 1851.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Preparations and planning for this coup took place at Saint-Cloud.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Among the conspirators were Jean-Gilbert Victor Fialin (a loyal companion of Louis-Napoléon), Charles de Morny (Louis-Napoléon's half-brother), and General Jacques Leroy de Saint Arnaud.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 14 October, Louis-Napoleon asked the Parliament to restore universal male suffrage but the request was turned down.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] His request for a reconsideration of the constitutional reform proposal was also turned down on 13 November.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Prepared to strike, Louis-Napoleon appointed General Saint-Arnaud as the Minister of War and a circular was issued reminding soldiers of their pledge of "passive obedience".
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Followers of the President were appointed to various important positions: General Magnan as the Commander of the Troops of Paris, and Maupas, Prefect of Haute-Garonne as Prefect of Police of Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Convinced that the coup was now inevitable after the latest refusal, Louis-Napoleon fixed the anniversary of the coronation of Napoleon in 1804, and the victory at Austerlitz in 1805, as the day for the coup.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The operation was christened Rubicon, alluding to Julius Caesar.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On the morning of 2 December, troops led by Saint-Arnaud occupied strategic points in Paris, from the Champs-Élysées to the Tuileries.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Top opposition leaders were arrested and six edicts promulgated to establish the rule of Louis-Napoleon.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The National Assembly was dissolved, and universal male suffrage restored.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Louis-Napoleon declared that a new constitution was being framed and said he intended to restore the "system established by the First Consul".
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Reacting to this coup, parliamentarians took refuge in the mayor's office of the 20th arrondissement of Paris, and 220 of them voted to oust Louis-Napoleon from power.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Most prominent among these were liberals like Remusat and moderates like Pascal Duprat, who were arrested soon after.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] A Parisian insurrection led by the likes of Victor Hugo and Victor Schoelcher erupted despite tight control by the army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 3 December parliamentarian Jean-Baptiste Baudin was killed, and on 4 December 200 more people fell victim to the suppression of the revolt.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The Italian journalist Ferdinando Petruccelli della Gattina was among the rebels and was expelled from France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] By evening, the revolt of Paris was suppressed and the city returned to normal.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] According to Victor Hugo the killings which followed on 4 December were arbitrary and anybody visible to the soldiers was shot at or bayoneted including women and children.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The coup triggered revolts in other places across France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 5 December, rebellions were reported in big cities, small towns and rural areas in the south-west of France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The department of Basses-Alpes even declared itself administered by a "Committee of Resistance" but the army, still loyal to the President, succeeded in quelling the rebellion.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] A total of 32 departments were put under a state of alert from 8 December and the rebellious areas were controlled in a few days.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Opponents were arrested and some were forced to flee.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Victor Hugo fled to Brussels, then Jersey, and finally settled with his family on the Channel Island of Guernsey at Hauteville House, where he would live in exile until Napoleon III's downfall in 1870 and collapse of the regime during the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] By the end of the rebellion, 26,000 people were arrested, 9,530 were sent to Algeria and 250 to the prison of Cayenne.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The Bonapartists were finally assured of a victory.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Generals Vaillant and Harispe became Marshals of France on 11 December.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] A referendum was organised to ratify the new order and the coup was portrayed as a security operation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] On 20 and 21 December, the French population were recorded as having voted for acceptance of the new regime by an overwhelming majority of 7,145,000 to 600,000, although the official tally and free nature of the vote were questioned by dissidents like Victor Hugo.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Bonaparte now had the power to draft a new constitution.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Following a referendum in December 1851, a new constitution was adopted in January 1852.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] It dramatically expanded the powers of the president, who was elected for a period of 10 years with no term limits.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] He not only possessed executive power, but was vested with the power of legislative initiative, thereby reducing the scope of the Parliament.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Bonaparte was automatically reelected to a fresh term as president.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] For all intents and purposes, he now held all governing power in the nation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The authoritarian republic proved to be only a stopgap, as Bonaparte immediately set about restoring the Empire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] In less than a year, following another referendum on 7 November 1852, the Second French Empire was proclaimed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] Again on the symbolic and historic date of 2 December, President Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte became Napoleon III, Emperor of the French.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1851-french-coup-d-état] The 1851 constitution concentrated so much power in Louis-Napoléon's hands that when the Empire was proclaimed, the only substantive changes to the document were to replace the word "president" with the word "emperor" and make the post hereditary.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] The **1st Guards Infantry Division** (German: **1.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] Garde-Infanterie-Division**) was a royal guard (later imperial guard) unit of the Prussian (and later) Imperial German Army and was stationed in Berlin.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] The division was created on September 5, 1818 when the guards brigades, which had been created in 1813 and were assigned to various commands, were grouped into a single formation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] Ernst Ludwig von Tippelskirch was appointed as the first commander of the division.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] The division was active during the Austro-Prussian War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] It was commanded by Generalmajor Constantin von Alvensleben and part of the Second Army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] During the Franco-Prussian War, the division was commanded by Generalmajor Alexander August Wilhelm von Pape.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] It was part of the Second Army, commanded by Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] Throughout the war 4 officers, 70 men, and 10 horses were killed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] By 1914 the division was subordinate to the Guards Corps of the Imperial German Army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] At the outbreak of the First World War it was commanded by Gen-Lt.
[src:franco-prussian-war/1st-guards-infantry-division-german-empire] In April of 1915 Prince Eitel Friedrich took command of the division until October of 1918, when he was relieved by Eduard von Jena.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:franco-prussian-war/8mm-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor was born in 1906 in Birkdale, Southport, which was then part of Lancashire, only child of cotton merchant Percy Lees Taylor and schoolmistress Constance Sumner Taylor (née Thompson).
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1919 his family returned to Ashton-on-Ribble, Preston, where both his parents' families had lived for several decades.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His wealthy parents held left-wing views, which he inherited.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Both his parents were pacifists who vocally opposed the First World War and sent their son to Quaker schools as a way of protesting against the war (his grandmother was from an old Quaker family).
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] These schools included The Downs School at Colwall and Bootham School in York.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Geoffrey Barraclough, a contemporary at Bootham School, remembered Taylor as "a most arresting, stimulating, vital personality, violently anti-bourgeois and anti-Christian".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1924, he went to Oriel College, Oxford, to study modern history.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] During his time as an undergraduate, in 1925 and 1926, he was the first student to hold the position of secretary of the junior common room.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In the 1920s, Taylor's mother, Constance, was a member of the Comintern while one of his uncles was a founder member of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Constance was a suffragette, feminist and advocate of free love who practised her teachings via a string of extramarital affairs, most notably with Henry Sara, a communist who in many ways became Taylor's surrogate father.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor has mentioned in his reminiscences that his mother was domineering, but his father enjoyed exasperating her by following his own ways.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor had a close relationship with his father and enjoyed his quirkiness.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor himself was recruited into the Communist Party of Great Britain by a friend of the family, the military historian Tom Wintringham, while at Oriel; a member from 1924 to 1926.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor broke with that party over what he considered to be its ineffective stand during the 1926 General Strike.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After leaving, he was an ardent supporter of the Labour Party for the rest of his life, remaining a member for over sixty years.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After leaving the Communist Party he visited the Soviet Union in 1925 and in 1934.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor graduated from Oxford in 1927 with a first-class honours degree.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After working briefly as a legal clerk, he began his post-graduate work, going to Vienna to study the impact of the Chartist movement on the Revolutions of 1848.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] When this topic turned out not to be feasible, he switched to studying the question of Italian unification over a two-year period.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] This resulted in his first book, *The Italian Problem in European Diplomacy, 1847–49* published in 1934.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor was a lecturer in history in the Victoria University of Manchester from 1930 to 1938.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He initially lived with his wife in an unfurnished flat on the top floor of an eighteenth-century house called The Limes, at 148 Wilmslow Road, which was set back from the street, opposite the entrance to Didsbury Park, at the southern end of Didsbury village.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] A few years later Taylor purchased a house in the village of Disley on the edge of the Peak District.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He became a Fellow of Magdalen College, Oxford, in 1938, a post he held until 1976.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was also a lecturer in modern history at the University of Oxford from 1938 to 1963.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] At Oxford he was such a popular speaker that he had to give his lectures at 8:30 a.m. to avoid the room becoming over-crowded.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1962, Taylor wrote in a review of *The Great Hunger: Ireland 1845–1849* by Cecil Woodham-Smith that: "All Ireland was a Belsen. ...
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The English governing class ran true to form.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1964, whilst he retained his college fellowship, the University of Oxford declined to renew Taylor's appointment as a university lecturer in modern history.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] This apparently sudden decision came in the aftermath of the controversy around his book *The Origins of the Second World War*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Moving to London, he became a lecturer at the Institute of Historical Research at University College London and at the Polytechnic of North London.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] An important step in Taylor's "rehabilitation" was a *festschrift* organised in his honour by Martin Gilbert in 1965.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was honoured with two more *festschriften*, in 1976 and 1986.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The *festschriften* were testaments to his popularity with his former students as receiving even a single *festschrift* is considered to be an extraordinary and rare honour.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] During the Second World War, Taylor served in the Home Guard and befriended émigré statesmen from Central Europe, such as the former Hungarian President Count Mihály Károlyi and Czechoslovak President Edvard Beneš.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] These friendships helped to enhance his understanding of the region.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His friendship with Beneš and Károlyi may help explain his sympathetic portrayal of them, in particular Károlyi, whom Taylor portrayed as a saintly figure.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor became friends with Hubert Ripka, the press attache for Beneš, who lived in Oxford.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Through him, he got to know President Beneš who lived in London.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor wrote that because Beneš was a President, "he was not allowed to brave the front line in London and had to live in a sovereign state at Aston Abbotts – a Rothschild house of, for them, a modest standard.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Bored and isolated, Beneš summoned an audience whatever he could and I was often swept over to Aston Abbots in the presidential car".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1943, Taylor wrote his first pamphlet, *Czechoslovakia's Place in a Free Europe*, explaining his view that Czechoslovakia would after the war serve as a "bridge" between the Western world and the Soviet Union.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] *Czechoslovakia's Place in a Free Europe* began as a lecture Taylor had given at the Czechoslovak Institute in London on 29 April 1943 and at the suggestion of Jan Masaryk was turned into a pamphlet to explain Czechoslovakia's situation to the British people.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Beneš during the present war has won for Czechoslovakia a secure future." During the same period, Taylor was employed by the Political Warfare Executive as an expert on Central Europe and frequently spoke on the radio and at various public meetings.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] During the war, he lobbied for British recognition of Josip Broz Tito's Partisans as the legitimate government of Yugoslavia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1979, Taylor resigned in protest from the British Academy over its dismissal of Anthony Blunt, who had been exposed as a Soviet spy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He married his first wife Margaret Adams in 1931.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] They had four children and divorced in 1951.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] For some time in the 1930s, he and his wife shared a house with the writer Malcolm Muggeridge and his wife Kitty.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] From the 1940s Margaret's infatuations with Robert Kee and Dylan Thomas pushed the couple towards separation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His second wife was Eve Crosland, the sister of Anthony Crosland MP, whom Taylor married in 1951; they had two children and divorced in 1974.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His third wife was the Hungarian historian Éva Haraszti.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor's first book, published in 1934, addressed the question of Italian unification *The Italian Problem in European Diplomacy, 1847–49*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] However, Taylor's speciality was in Central European, British and diplomatic history.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was especially interested in the Habsburg dynasty and Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His main mentors in this period were the Austrian-born historian Alfred Francis Pribram and the Polish-born historian Sir Lewis Namier.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor's earlier writings reflected Pribram's favourable opinion of the Habsburgs; however, his 1941 book *The Habsburg Monarchy 1809–1918* (published in a revised edition in 1948) showed the influence of Namier's unfavourable views.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In *The Habsburg Monarchy*, Taylor stated that the Habsburgs saw their realms entirely as a tool for foreign policy and thus could never build a genuine nation-state.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] To hold their realm together, they resorted to playing one ethnic group off against another and promoted German and Magyar hegemony over the other ethnic groups in Austria-Hungary.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1954 he published his masterpiece, *The Struggle for Mastery in Europe 1848–1918*, and followed it up with *The Trouble Makers* in 1957, a critical study of British foreign policy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] *The Trouble Makers* was a celebration of those who had criticised the government over foreign policy, a subject dear to his heart.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] *The Trouble Makers* had originally been the Ford Lectures in 1955 and was his favourite book by far.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] When invited to deliver the Ford Lectures, he was initially at a loss for a topic; and it was his friend Alan Bullock who suggested the topic of foreign policy dissent.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The recurring theme of accidents deciding history appeared in Taylor's best-selling 1955 biography of Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1961, he published his most controversial book, *The Origins of the Second World War*, which earned him a reputation as a revisionist.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Gordon Martel notes that "it made a profound impact.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In the book Taylor argued against the widespread belief that the outbreak of the Second World War (specifically between Germany, Poland, the United Kingdom and France, September 1939) was the result of an intentional plan on the part of Adolf Hitler.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He began his book with the statement that too many people have accepted uncritically what he called the "Nuremberg Thesis", that the Second World War was the result of criminal conspiracy by a small gang comprising Hitler and his associates.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor's thesis was that Hitler was not the demoniacal figure of popular imagination but in foreign affairs a normal German leader.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Citing Fritz Fischer, he argued that the foreign policy of Nazi Germany was the same as those of the Weimar Republic and the German Empire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Moreover, in a partial break with his view of German history advocated in *The Course of German History*, he argued that Hitler was not just a mainstream German leader but also a mainstream Western leader.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] As a normal Western leader, Hitler was no better or worse than Gustav Stresemann, Neville Chamberlain or Édouard Daladier.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His argument was that Hitler wished to make Germany the strongest power in Europe but he did not want or plan war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The outbreak of war in 1939 was an unfortunate accident caused by mistakes on everyone's part and was not a part of Hitler's plan.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor portrayed Hitler as a grasping opportunist with no beliefs other than the pursuit of power and anti-Semitism.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He argued that Hitler did not possess any sort of programme and his foreign policy was one of drift and seizing chances as they offered themselves.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He did not consider Hitler's anti-Semitism unique: he argued that millions of Germans were just as ferociously anti-Semitic as Hitler and there was no reason to single out Hitler for sharing the beliefs of millions of others.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Though Taylor argued that the Second World War was not inevitable and that the Versailles Treaty was nowhere near as harsh as contemporaries like John Maynard Keynes believed, what he regarded as a flawed peace settlement made the war more likely than not.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1965 he rebounded from the controversy surrounding *The Origins of the Second World War* with the spectacular success of his book *English History 1914–1945*, his only venture into social and cultural history, where he offered a loving, affectionate portrayal of the years between 1914 and 1945.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] *English History 1914–1945* was an enormous best-seller and in its first year in print sold more than all of the previous volumes of the *Oxford History of England* combined.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Though he held many anti-British views, especially in regard to Ireland, he was very proud to be British and more specifically English.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was fond of stressing his nonconformist Northern English background and saw himself as part of a grand tradition of radical dissent that he regarded as the real glorious history of England.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1964 Taylor wrote the introduction for *The Reichstag Fire* by the journalist Fritz Tobias.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He thus became the first English-language historian and the first historian after Hans Mommsen to accept the conclusions of the book, that the Nazis had not caused the *Reichstag* fire and that Marinus van der Lubbe had acted alone.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Tobias and Taylor argued that the new Nazi government had been looking for something to increase its share of the vote in the elections of 5 March 1933, so as to activate the Enabling Act, and that van der Lubbe had serendipitously (for the Nazis) provided it by burning down the Reichstag.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Even without the fire, the Nazis were quite determined to destroy German democracy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In Taylor's opinion, van der Lubbe had made their task easier by providing a pretext.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The German Communist propaganda chief Willi Münzenberg and his OGPU handlers had manufactured the evidence implicating the Nazis in the arson.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Tobias and Taylor pointed out that the so-called "secret tunnels" that supposedly gave the Nazis access to the *Reichstag* were in fact tunnels for water piping.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] At the time Taylor was widely attacked by many other historians for endorsing what was considered to be a self-evident perversion of established historical facts.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In his 1969 book *War by Timetable*, Taylor examined the origins of the First World War, concluding that though all of the great powers wished to increase their own power relative to the others, none consciously sought war before 1914.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Instead, he argued that all of the great powers believed that if they possessed the ability to mobilise their armed forces faster than any of the others, this would serve as a sufficient deterrent to avoid war and allow them to achieve their foreign policy aims.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Thus, the general staffs of the great powers developed elaborate timetables to mobilise faster than any of their rivals.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] When the crisis broke in 1914, though none of the statesmen of Europe wanted a world war, the need to mobilise faster than potential rivals created an inexorable movement towards war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Thus Taylor claimed that the leaders of 1914 became prisoners of the logic of the mobilisation timetables and the timetables that were meant to serve as deterrent to war instead relentlessly brought war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In the 1950s and 1960s, Taylor befriended Lord Beaverbrook and later wrote his biography in 1972.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Beaverbrook, Canadian in origin, was a Conservative who believed strongly in the British Empire and whose entry into politics was in support of Bonar Law, a Conservative leader strongly connected with the establishment of Northern Ireland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite the disdain for most politicians expressed in his writings, Taylor was fascinated by politics and politicians and often cultivated relations with those who possessed power.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Beside Lord Beaverbrook, whose company Taylor very much enjoyed, his favourite politician was the Labour Party leader Michael Foot, whom he often described as the greatest Prime Minister Britain never had.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor also wrote significant introductions to British editions of Marx's *The Communist Manifesto* and of *Ten Days that Shook the World*, by John Reed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He had long been an advocate of a treaty with the Soviet Union so British Communists expected him to be friendly.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1963, the British Communist Party, which held the copyright to *Ten Days that Shook the World* in the United Kingdom, offered Taylor the opportunity to write the introduction to a new edition.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The introduction Taylor wrote was fairly sympathetic towards the Bolsheviks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The British Communist Party rejected Taylor's introduction as anti-Soviet.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] When the copyright expired in 1977 and a non-Communist publisher reissued the book, asking Taylor to write the introduction, he strengthened some of his criticisms.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor also wrote the introduction for *Fighter: The True Story of the Battle of Britain* by Len Deighton.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Starting in 1931, Taylor worked as book reviewer for the *Manchester Guardian*, and from 1957 he was a columnist with the *Observer*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1951 Taylor made his first move into mass-market journalism, spending just over a year as a columnist at the tabloid *Sunday Pictorial*, later renamed the *Sunday Mirror*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His first article was an attack on the stance of the United Nations during the Korean War, in which he argued that the UN was merely a front for American policy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After leaving the *Sunday Pictorial* in 1952, in the wake of editor Philip Zec's dismissal, he began writing a weekly column the following year for the *Daily Herald* until 1956.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] From 1957 until 1982 he wrote for the *Sunday Express*, owned by his friend and patron Lord Beaverbrook.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] At a time when the relationship with the EEC was a major issue in Britain, Taylor's pro-Commonwealth Euroscepticism became a common theme in many of his articles.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Other frequent targets were the BBC, the anti-smoking lobby and, reversing his earlier stance, the motor car, with Taylor calling for all private motor vehicles to be banned.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The Second World War gave Taylor the opportunity to branch out from print journalism, initially into radio and then later television.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] On 17 March 1942 Taylor made the first of seven appearances on *The World at War – Your Questions Answered* broadcast by BBC Forces' Radio.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After the war Taylor became one of the first television historians.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His appearances began with his role as a panellist on the BBC's *In The News* from 1950 to 1954.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Here he was noted for his argumentative style: in one episode he declined to acknowledge the presence of the other panellists.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The press came to refer to him as the "sulky don" and in 1954 he was dropped.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] From 1955 Taylor was a panellist on ITV's rival discussion programme *Free Speech*, where he remained until the series ended in 1961.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1957, 1957–1958 and 1961 he made a number of half-hour programmes on ITV in which he lectured without notes on a variety of topics, such as the Russian Revolution of 1917 and the First World War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite earlier strong feelings against the BBC, he lectured for a BBC historical series in 1961 and made more series for it in 1963, 1976, 1977 and 1978.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He also hosted additional series for ITV in 1964, 1966 and 1967.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In *Edge of Britain* in 1980 he toured the towns of northern England.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor's final TV appearance was in the series *How Wars End* in 1985, where the effects of Parkinson's disease on him were apparent.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor had a famous rivalry with the historian Hugh Trevor-Roper, with whom he often debated on television.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] One of the more famous exchanges took place in 1961.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The origins of the dispute went back to 1957 when the Regius Professorship for History at Oxford was vacant.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite their divergent political philosophies, Taylor and Trevor-Roper had been friends since the early 1950s, but with the possibility of the Regius Professorship, both men lobbied for it.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The Conservative Prime Minister Harold Macmillan awarded the chair to the Tory Trevor-Roper rather than the Labourite Taylor.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In addition, a number of the other Oxford dons had felt that Taylor's profile in journalism was "demeaning" to the historian's craft and had lobbied against him.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In public, Taylor declared that he would never have accepted any honour from a government that had "the blood of Suez on its hands".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In private, he was furious with Trevor-Roper for holding an honour that Taylor considered rightfully his.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Adding to Taylor's rancour was that he had arrived at Oxford a decade before Trevor-Roper.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] From then on, Taylor never missed a chance to disparage Trevor-Roper's character or scholarship.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The famously combative Trevor-Roper reciprocated.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The feud was given much publicity by the media, not so much because of the merits of their disputes but rather because their acrimonious debates on television made for entertaining viewing.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Likewise, the various articles written by Taylor and Trevor-Roper denouncing each other's scholarship, in which both men's considerable powers of invective were employed with maximum effect, made for entertaining reading.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Beyond that, it was fashionable to portray the dispute between Taylor and Trevor-Roper as a battle between generations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor, with his populist, irreverent style, was nearly a decade older than Trevor-Roper, but was represented by the media as a symbol of the younger generation that was coming of age in the 1950s–1960s.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Trevor-Roper, who was unabashedly old-fashioned (he was one of the last Oxford dons to lecture wearing his professor's robes) and inclined to behave in a manner that the media portrayed as pompous and conceited, was seen as a symbol of the older generation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] A subtle but important difference in the style between the two historians was their manner of addressing each other during their TV debates: Trevor-Roper always addressed Taylor as "Mr Taylor" or just "Taylor", while Taylor always addressed Trevor-Roper as "Hugh".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Another frequent sparring partner on TV for Taylor was the writer Malcolm Muggeridge.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The frequent television appearances helped to make Taylor the most famous British historian of the 20th century.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He featured in a cameo in the 1981 film *Time Bandits* and was satirised in an episode of *Monty Python's Flying Circus*, in which a scantily clad woman (identified by an onscreen caption as "A.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor, Historian"), dubbed over with a man's voice, delivers a lecture on "Eighteenth Century Social Reform".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Throughout his life, Taylor took public stands on the great issues of his time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In the early 1930s, he was in a left-wing pacifist group called the Manchester Peace Council, for which he frequently spoke in public.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Until 1936, Taylor was an opponent of British rearmament as he felt that a re-armed Britain would ally itself with Germany against the Soviet Union.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] However, after 1936, he resigned from the Manchester Peace Council, urged British rearmament in the face of what he considered to be the Nazi menace and advocated an Anglo-Soviet alliance to contain Germany.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After 1936, he also fervently criticised appeasement, a stance that he disavowed in 1961.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1938, he denounced the Munich Agreement at several rallies and may have written several leaders in the *Manchester Guardian* criticising it; later, he would compare the smaller number of Czechoslovak dead with the number of Polish dead.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In October 1938, Taylor attracted particular controversy by a speech he gave at a dinner held every October to commemorate a protest by a group of Oxford dons against James II in 1688, an event that was an important prelude to the Glorious Revolution.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He denounced the Munich Agreement and those who supported it, warning the assembled dons that if action were not taken immediately to resist Nazi Germany, then they might all soon be living under the rule of a much greater tyrant than James II.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Throughout his life, Taylor was sympathetic to the foreign policy of the Soviet Union and, after 1941, was overjoyed to have the Soviet Union as Britain's ally, as this was the realisation of his desire for an Anglo-Soviet alliance.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The Second World War further increased Taylor's pro-Soviet feelings, as he was always profoundly grateful for the Red Army's role in destroying Nazi Germany.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite his pro-Soviet views, he was strongly critical of Stalinism, and in 1948 he attended and did his best to sabotage a Stalinist cultural congress in Wrocław, Poland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His speech, which was broadcast live on Polish radio and via speakers on the streets of Wrocław, about the right of everyone to hold different views from those who hold power, was enthusiastically received by the delegates and was met with thunderous applause.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The speech was clearly intended as a rebuttal of a speech given by the Soviet writer Alexander Fadeyev the previous day, who had demanded obedience on the part of everyone to Joseph Stalin.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] As a socialist, Taylor saw the capitalist system as wrong on practical and moral grounds, although he rejected the Marxist view that capitalism was responsible for wars and conflicts.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He felt that the status quo in the West was highly unstable, prone to accident and prevented a just and moral international system from coming into being.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Moreover, Taylor was enraged by the decision of the Western powers, which he blamed on the US, to re-build and establish the West German state in the late 1940s, which Taylor saw as laying the foundations for a Fourth Reich that would one day plunge the world back into war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He also blamed the United States for the Cold War, and in the 1950s and 1960s was one of the leading lights of the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor never visited the United States, despite receiving many invitations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1950, he was again temporarily banned by the BBC when he attempted to deliver a radio address against British participation in the Korean War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] After a public outcry, the BBC relented and allowed him to deliver his address.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1956 Taylor demonstrated against the Suez War, though not the Soviet crushing of the 1956 Hungarian Revolution, which he believed had saved Hungary from a return to the rule of Admiral Miklós Horthy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He also championed Israel, which he saw as a model socialist democracy threatened by reactionary Arab dictatorships.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor was also opposed to, and condemned, the US intervention in the Vietnam War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor was also opposed to the British Empire and against Britain's participation in the European Economic Community and NATO.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In an interview with Irish State radio in April 1976, Taylor argued that the British presence in Northern Ireland was perpetuating the conflict there.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor claimed the best solution would be for an "armed push" by the Irish nationalists to drive out the one million Ulster Protestants from Ireland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He cited as a successful precedent the expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia after the Second World War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] On the question of whether there would be a civil war should Britain quit Northern Ireland, Taylor answered: "What we have, after all, is an incipient civil war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] To put it brutally, if there were a civil war in Northern Ireland, and I am not convinced that there would be, quite a lot of people would be killed and the war would be decided within a few months.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Spread over the years, probably more people have been killed".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1980 Taylor resigned from the British Academy in protest against the expulsion of the art historian and Soviet spy Anthony Blunt, which he saw as an act of McCarthyism.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Closer to his work as a historian, Taylor espoused less government secrecy and, paradoxically for a staunch leftist, fought for more privately owned television stations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His experiences with being banned by the BBC had led him to appreciate the value of having many broadcasters.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In regard to government archives, Taylor took part in a successful attempt to lobby the British government to replace the 50-year rule with a 30-year rule.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1944, he was temporarily banned from the BBC following complaints about a series of lectures he gave on air in which he gave full vent to his anti-German feelings.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In his 1945 book, *The Course of German History*, he argued that National Socialism was the inevitable product of the entire history of the Germans going back to the days of the Germanic tribes.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was an early champion of what has since been called the *Sonderweg* (Special Way) interpretation of German history, that German culture and society developed over the centuries in such a way as to make Nazi Germany inevitable.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Moreover, he argued that there was a symbiotic relationship between Hitler and the German people, with Adolf Hitler needing the Germans to fulfil his dreams of conquest and the German people needing Hitler to fulfil their dreams of subjugation of their neighbours.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In particular, he accused the Germans of waging an endless *Drang nach Osten* against their Slavic neighbours since the days of Charlemagne.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] For Taylor, Nazi racial imperialism was a continuation of policies pursued by every German ruler.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] *The Course of German History* was a best-seller in both the United Kingdom and the United States; it was the success of this book that made Taylor's reputation in the United States.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Its success also marked the beginning of the breach between Taylor and his mentor Namier, who wanted to write a similar book.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] By the 1950s, relations between Taylor and Namier had noticeably cooled and in his 1983 autobiography, *A Personal History*, Taylor, though acknowledging a huge intellectual debt to Namier, portrayed him as a pompous bore.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor's approach to history was the larger the audience the better.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He felt that history should be open to all and enjoyed being called the "People's Historian" and the "Everyman's Historian".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He usually favoured an anti-great man theory, history being made for the most part by towering figures of stupidity rather than of genius.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In his view, leaders did not make history; instead they reacted to events – what happened in the past was due to sequences of blunders and errors that were largely outside anyone's control.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] To the extent that anyone made anything happen in history, it was only through their mistakes.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Though Taylor normally preferred to portray leaders as fools blundering their way forward, he did think that individuals sometimes could play a positive role in history; his heroes were Vladimir Lenin and David Lloyd George.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] But for Taylor, people like Lloyd George and Lenin were the exceptions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite Taylor's increasing ambivalence toward appeasement from the late 1950s, which became explicitly evident in his 1961 book *Origins of the Second World War*, Winston Churchill remained another of his heroes.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In *English History 1914–1945* (1965), he famously concluded his biographical footnote of Churchill with the phrase "the saviour of his country".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Another person Taylor admired was the historian E.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Carr, who was his favourite historian and a good friend.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His narratives used irony and humour to entertain as well as inform.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He examined history from odd angles, exposing what he considered to be the pomposities of historical characters.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was famed for "Taylorisms": witty, epigrammatic and sometimes cryptic remarks that were meant to expose what he considered to be the absurdities and paradoxes of modern international relations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] An example is in his television piece *Mussolini* (1970), in which he said the dictator "kept up with his work – by doing none"; or, about Metternich's political philosophies: "Most men could do better while shaving".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] His determination to bring history to everyone drove his frequent appearances on radio and later on television.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] He was also careful to puncture any aura of infallibility that historians might have.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] I followed their example except the poor were always right and the rich always wrong – a judgement that happens to be correct historically.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Some of the details were also a parody, as for instance the solemn discussion as when 'Fuck' attained literary though not conversational respectability.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] I had more fun writing *English History 1914–1945* than in writing any of my other books".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor has been credited with coining the term "the Establishment" in a 1953 book review, but this is disputed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] On 29 August 1953, in reviewing a biography of William Cobbett in *New Statesman*, Taylor wrote "The Establishment draws in recruits from outside as soon as they are ready to conform to its standards and become respectable.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In 1967, Taylor wrote an article for the *Sunday Express* in which he argued that speed limits had made absolutely no positive difference to road safety and that "on the contrary, [speed limits] tend to increase the risks and dangers".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor went on to claim "I have been driving a car for 45 years.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] I have consistently ignored all the various speed limits.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Never once have I encountered the slightest risk as a result." The article caused a member of the public to lodge a complaint with the Press Council, on the grounds that Taylor's remarks "amount[ed] to an indirect incitement to drivers to break the law".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The Council eventually rejected the complaint and ruled that "while Mr Taylor's views are controversial, he has an unchallengeable right to express them".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Other historians who criticised *The Origins of the Second World War* included: Isaac Deutscher, Barbara Tuchman, Ian Morrow, Gerhard Weinberg, Elizabeth Wiskemann, W.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Medlicott, Tim Mason, John Lukacs, Karl Dietrich Bracher, Frank Freidel, Harry Hinsley, John Wheeler-Bennett, Golo Mann, Lucy Dawidowicz, Gordon A.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Rowse, Raymond Sontag, Andreas Hillgruber and Yehuda Bauer.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Rowse, who had once been a close friend of Taylor's, attacked him with an intensity and vehemence that was second only to Trevor-Roper's.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In addition, several historians wrote books on the origins of the Second World War with the aim of refuting Taylor's thesis.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor was angered by some of the criticism, especially the implication that he had set out to exonerate Hitler, writing that "to the best of my recollection, those who now display indignation against me were not active [against appeasement] on the public platform".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Some notable examples include Gerhard Weinberg's two-volume *The Foreign Policy of Hitler's Germany* and Andreas Hillgruber's *Deutschlands Rolle in der Vorgeschichte der beiden Weltkriege* [*Germany's Role in the Background to Both World Wars*], translated as *Germany and the Two World Wars*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The issue of misinterpretation is also addressed in Gordon A.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Craig's book *Germany: 1866–1945*, where it is argued that Taylor dismissed Hitler's foreign policy, as presented in *Mein Kampf*, and in particular, the remilitarisation of the Rhineland, as a jumble of idle thoughts written down under the impact of the French occupation of the Ruhr.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] As angry as the reaction in Britain was to *The Origins of the Second World War*, it was greater when the book was published in January 1962 in the United States.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] With the exception of Harry Elmer Barnes and Murray Rothbard, every American historian who reviewed Taylor's book gave it a negative review.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite the best efforts of Barnes and his protégé David Hoggan to recruit Taylor to their cause, Taylor always made clear that he wanted nothing to do with either Barnes or Hoggan.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Despite the criticism, *The Origins of the Second World War* is regarded as a watershed in the historiography of the origins of the Second World War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] In response to Taylor's argument that Hitler had no programme because his foreign policy seemed to operate in a haphazard and slapdash way, Taylor's critics such as Trevor-Roper construed a theorem in which Hitler held "consistent aims" but sought to achieve them via "flexible methods".
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor drew a picture of Benito Mussolini as a great showman, but also as an inept leader with no beliefs.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] The first part of this picture has not been generally challenged by historians, but the second part has.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Taylor has been criticised for promoting the *La décadence* view of the French Third Republic.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] This historical concept portrays the Third Republic as a decadent state, forever on the verge of collapse.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Of all the French governments of the interwar era, only the Popular Front government of Léon Blum was presented sympathetically by Taylor, which he praised for carrying out what he regarded as long overdue social reforms.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p01] Many experts in French history have admitted that there is a kernel of truth to Taylor's picture of France but have complained that Taylor presented French politics and society in such a manner as to border on caricature.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] Taylor was badly injured in 1984 when he was run over by a car while crossing Old Compton Street in London.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] The effect of the accident led to his retirement in 1985.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] In his last years, he endured Parkinson's disease, which left him incapable of writing.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] His last public appearance was at his 80th birthday, in 1986, when a group of his former students, including Sir Martin Gilbert, Alan Sked, Norman Davies and Paul Kennedy, organised a public reception in his honour.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] He had, with considerable difficulty, memorised a short speech, which he delivered in a manner that managed to hide the fact that his memory and mind had been permanently damaged by Parkinson's.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] In 1987, he entered a nursing home in Barnet, London, where he died on 7 September 1990 aged 84.
[src:franco-prussian-war/a-j-p-taylor-p02] He was cremated at Golders Green Crematorium.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Divisional-General **Charles Abel Douay** (2 March 1809 – 4 August 1870) was a French Army officer who served in numerous military campaigns during the 19th century.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] During the Franco-Prussian War, he was recalled to active duty and killed in action at the age of sixty-one while fighting against Prussian forces near Wissembourg.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Charles Abel Douay was born in the city of Draguignan on 2 March 1809.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] He became a well-known and well-respected military officer, described roundly as an "able" and "intrepid" soldier.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] He served in the French conquest of Algeria, Crimean War, second French intervention in Mexico and Second Italian War of Independence.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] He was the elder brother of General Félix Douay, who was also a distinguished career officer.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] (Because of their similar names and overlapping careers, the elder Douay is most frequently referred to as "Abel Douay".) At the beginning of the Franco-Prussian War, Abel Douay had already settled into his position as president of the military academy at Saint-Cyr.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Recalled to active duty at the outbreak of war in 1870, the academy president was given command of a division under Marshal Patrice de Mac-Mahon at the frontline, and on the first day of the first battle of the war, Douay was killed in combat, hit by an artillery explosion.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] The subsequent Battle of Wissembourg (4 August 1870) proved a disaster for the French.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Demoralized by the loss of their commander, Douay's outnumbered division fell back.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] By the end of the month, a crushing loss at the Battle of Sedan eliminated Mac-Mahon's entire army and, with it, the Second French Empire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] On 3 August 1870, the 61-year-old Douay led the forward division of Mac-Mahon's army group, a force of approximately 8,600, into the frontier town of Wissembourg in Alsace, the border region between the two combatant nations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Faulty intelligence had characterized the Prussians' border positions as weak and unready, and Douay's superiors felt confident that he could repulse any enemy probes while making use of the town's badly needed food and resources.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] At 8:30am the next day, batteries of undetected Prussian artillery began pummelling the French position, and though Douay attempted a rapid defensive posture, the advantage of surprise had been devastatingly complete.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] The massive scale of the attack quickly became apparent – total Prussian forces are estimated between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] By mid-morning Douay was already organizing for a withdrawal when he was killed by a burst of artillery.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Some writers have mistakenly reported that he was hit by gunfire, but most historians concur that he died from a shell which exploded in the nearby ammunition magazine of one of the French grapeshot cannon.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] The withdrawal turned into a rout, with over 1,000 French soldiers killed and a thousand more taken prisoner.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Douay's death was a deeply demoralizing blow to the French army and gave a profound shock to the nation at large.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Few, however, were as shocked as Napoleon III, who immediately issued a flurry of new orders reconstituting the army's command structure and strategic guidelines.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Félix Douay was stationed along the same front as his older brother and fought at Sedan until the final surrender.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] He too served as a field commander, leader of the French 7th Corps.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] Douay was buried in a stately tomb just outside Wissembourg together with many of his fallen soldiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] A large monument to the battle was erected near his tomb at the end of the First World War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] 20 years after the battle, an apocryphal story was published in Germany proffering a different story of Douay's death: a German "eyewitness" claimed that the general had been shot by one of his own men, allegedly for ordering a retreat.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] This story perhaps derived from the reported words of Frederick III who, advancing through the battlefield, had come upon Douay's corpse and made the bald observation that the general had died beyond the range of German rifle fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/abel-douay] A solemn portrayal of this scene was later created by the Prussian history painter Anton von Werner.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The **Franco-Prussian War**, occasionally known as the **Franco-German War**, and sometimes referred to in France as the **War of 1870**, was a conflict between France and the North German Confederation led by Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Lasting from 19 July 1870 to 28 January 1871, the conflict was caused primarily by France's determination to reassert its dominant position in continental Europe, which appeared in question following the decisive Prussian victory over Austria in 1866.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The internal Ems dispatch reported this to Berlin on July 13; Prussian chancellor Otto von Bismarck quickly then made it public with altered wording.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Thus the French newspapers for July 14, the French national holiday contained translations of Bismarck's press release, but not a report from their own ambassador.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A crowd in the streets of Paris demanded war, and soon French mobilization was ordered.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] According to some historians, Prussian chancellor Otto von Bismarck deliberately provoked the French into declaring war on Prussia in order to induce four independent southern German states—Baden, Württemberg, Bavaria and Hesse-Darmstadt—to join the North German Confederation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Other historians contend that Bismarck exploited the circumstances as they unfolded.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] All agree that Bismarck recognized the potential for new German alliances, given the situation as a whole.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] France mobilised its army on 15 July 1870, leading the North German Confederation to respond with its own mobilisation later that day.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 16 July 1870, the French parliament voted to declare war on Prussia; France invaded German territory on 2 August.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German coalition mobilised its troops much more effectively than the French and invaded northeastern France on 4 August.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] German forces were superior in numbers, training, and leadership and made more effective use of modern technology, particularly railways and artillery.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] German forces fought and defeated new French armies in northern France, then besieged Paris for over four months before it fell on 28 January 1871, effectively ending the war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] In the final days of the war, with German victory all but assured, the German states proclaimed their union as the German Empire under the Prussian king Wilhelm I and Chancellor Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With the notable exceptions of Austria and German Switzerland, the vast majority of German-speakers were united under a nation-state for the first time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Following an armistice with France, the Treaty of Frankfurt was signed on 10 May 1871, giving Germany billions of francs in war indemnity, as well as most of Alsace and parts of Lorraine, which became the Imperial Territory of Alsace-Lorraine (*Reichsland Elsaß-Lothringen*).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] By hastening German unification, the war significantly altered the balance of power on the continent, with the new German state supplanting France as the dominant European land power.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bismarck maintained great authority in international affairs for two decades, developing a reputation for *Realpolitik* that raised Germany's global stature and influence.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] In France, it brought a final end to imperial rule and began the first lasting republican government.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Resentment over the French government's handling of the war and its aftermath triggered the Paris Commune, a revolutionary uprising which seized and held power for two months before its suppression; the event would influence the politics and policies of the Third Republic.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The causes of the Franco-Prussian War are rooted in the events surrounding the lead up to the unification of the German states under Otto von Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] France had gained the status of being the dominant power of continental Europe as a result of the Franco-Austrian War of 1859.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] During the Austro-Prussian War of 1866, the Empress Eugénie, Foreign Minister Drouyn de Lhuys and War Minister Jacques Louis Randon were concerned that the power of Prussia might overtake that of France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] They unsuccessfully urged Napoleon to mass troops at France's eastern borders while the bulk of the Prussian armies were still engaged in Bohemia as a warning that no territorial changes could be effected in Germany without consulting France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] As a result of Prussia's annexation of several German states which had sided with Austria during the war and the formation of the North German Confederation under Prussia's aegis, French public opinion stiffened and now demanded more firmness as well as territorial compensations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] As a result, Napoleon demanded from Prussia a return to the French borders of 1814, with the annexation of Luxembourg, most of Saarland, and the Bavarian Palatinate.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bismarck flatly refused what he disdainfully termed France's *politique des pourboires* ("tipping policy").
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] He then communicated Napoleon III's written territorial demands to Bavaria and the other southern German states of Württemberg, Baden and Hesse-Darmstadt, which hastened the conclusion of defensive military alliances with these states.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] France had been strongly opposed to any further alliance of German states, which would have threatened French continental dominance.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The only result of French policy was the consent of Prussia to nominal independence for Saxony, Bavaria, Wurttemberg, Baden, and Hessia-Darmstadt.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This was a small victory, and one without appeal to a French public which wanted territory and a French army which wanted revenge.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The situation did not suit either France, which unexpectedly found itself next to the militarily powerful Prussian-led North German Confederation, or Prussia, whose foremost objective was to complete the process of uniting the German states under its control.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Thus, war between the two powers since 1866 was only a matter of time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] In Prussia, some officials considered a war against France both inevitable and necessary to arouse German nationalism in those states that would allow the unification of a great German empire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The immediate cause of the war was the candidacy of Leopold of Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen to the throne of Spain after the fall of Isabella II in 1868.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] France feared an encirclement resulting from an alliance between Prussia and Spain.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bismarck's summary, as mistranslated by the French press Havas, made it sound as if the king had treated the French envoy in a demeaning fashion, which inflamed public opinion in France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] French historians François Roth and Pierre Milza argue that Napoleon III was pressured by a bellicose press and public opinion and thus sought war in response to France's diplomatic failures to obtain any territorial gains following the Austro-Prussian War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon III believed he would win a conflict with Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Many in his court, such as Empress Eugénie, also wanted a victorious war to resolve growing domestic political problems, restore France as the undisputed leading power in Europe, and ensure the long-term survival of the House of Bonaparte.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A national plebiscite held on 8 May 1870, which returned results overwhelmingly in favor of the Emperor's domestic agenda gave the impression that the regime was politically popular and in a position to confront Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Within days of the plebiscite, France's pacifist Foreign Minister Napoléon, comte Daru, was replaced by Agenor, duc de Gramont, a fierce opponent of Prussia who, as French Ambassador to Austria in 1866, had advocated an Austro-French military alliance against Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon III's worsening health problems made him less and less capable of reining in Empress Eugénie, Gramont and the other members of the war party, known collectively as the "mameluks".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] For Bismarck, the nomination of Gramont was seen as "a highly bellicose symptom".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Ems telegram of 13 July 1870 had exactly the effect on French public opinion that Bismarck had intended.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] "This text produced the effect of a red flag on the Gallic bull", Bismarck later wrote.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Gramont, the French foreign minister, declared that he felt "he had just received a slap".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The leader of the monarchists in Parliament, Adolphe Thiers, spoke for moderation, arguing that France had won the diplomatic battle and there was no reason for war, but he was drowned out by cries that he was a traitor and a Prussian.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon's new prime minister, Emile Ollivier, declared that France had done all that it could humanly and honorably do to prevent the war, and that he accepted the responsibility "with a light heart".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A crowd of 15,000–20,000 people, carrying flags and patriotic banners, marched through the streets of Paris, demanding war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] French mobilization was ordered early on 15 July.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Upon receiving news of the French mobilization, the North German Confederation mobilized on the night of 15–16 July, while Bavaria and Baden did likewise on 16 July and Württemberg on 17 July.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 19 July 1870, the French sent a declaration of war to the Prussian government.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The southern German states immediately sided with Prussia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleonic France had no documented alliance with other powers and entered the war virtually without allies.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The calculation was for a victorious offensive, which, as the French Foreign Minister Gramont stated, was "the only way for France to lure the wary Austrians, Italians and Danes into the French alliance".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The involvement of Russia on the side of France was not considered by her at all, since Russia made the lifting of restrictions on its naval construction on the Black Sea imposed on Russia by the Treaty of Paris following the Crimean War a precondition for the union.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] But Imperial France was not ready to do this.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] "Bonaparte did not dare to encroach on the Paris Treaty: the worse things turned out in the present, the more precious the heritage of the past became".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French Army consisted in peacetime of approximately 426,000 soldiers, some of them regulars, others conscripts who until March 1869 were selected by ballot and served for the comparatively long period of seven years.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Some of them were veterans of previous French campaigns in the Crimean War, Algeria, the Franco-Austrian War in Italy, and in the Mexican campaign.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] However, following the "Seven Weeks War" between Prussia and Austria four years earlier, it had been calculated that, with commitments in Algeria and elsewhere, the French Army could field only 288,000 men to face the Prussian Army, when potentially 1,000,000 would be required.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Under Marshal Adolphe Niel, urgent reforms were made.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Universal conscription and a shorter period of service gave increased numbers of reservists, who would swell the army to a planned strength of 800,000 on mobilisation.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Those who for any reason were not conscripted were to be enrolled in the *Garde Mobile*, a militia with a nominal strength of 400,000.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] However, the Franco-Prussian War broke out before these reforms could be completely implemented.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The mobilisation of reservists was chaotic and resulted in large numbers of stragglers, while the *Garde Mobile* were generally untrained and often mutinous.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] French infantry were equipped with the breech-loading Chassepot rifle, one of the most modern mass-produced firearms in the world at the time, with 1,037,555 available in French inventories.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With a rubber ring seal and a smaller bullet, the Chassepot had a maximum effective range of some 1,500 metres (4,900 ft) with a short reloading time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] French tactics emphasised the defensive use of the Chassepot rifle in trench-warfare style fighting—the so-called *feu de bataillon*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French also obtained some obsolete Springfield Model 1866 and Spanish trapdoor rifles, issuing them to the *Armée de la Loire* and *Gardes Mobiles*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The artillery was equipped with rifled, muzzle-loaded La Hitte guns.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The army also possessed a precursor to the machine-gun: the mitrailleuse, which could unleash significant, concentrated firepower but nevertheless lacked range and was comparatively immobile, and thus prone to being easily overrun.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The mitrailleuse was mounted on an artillery gun carriage and grouped in batteries in a similar fashion to cannon.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The army was nominally led by Napoleon III, with Marshals François Achille Bazaine and Patrice de MacMahon in command of the field armies.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] However, there was no previously arranged plan of campaign in place.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The only campaign plan prepared between 1866 and 1870 was a defensive one.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German army comprised that of the North German Confederation led by the Kingdom of Prussia, and the South German states drawn in under the secret clause of the preliminary peace of Nikolsburg, 26 July 1866, and formalised in the Treaty of Prague, 23 August 1866.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Recruitment and organisation of the various armies were almost identical, and based on the concept of conscripting annual classes of men who then served in the regular regiments for a fixed term before being moved to the reserves.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This process gave a theoretical peace time strength of 382,000 and a wartime strength of about 1,189,000.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] German tactics emphasised encirclement battles like Cannae and using artillery offensively whenever possible.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Rather than advancing in a column or line formation, Prussian infantry moved in small groups that were harder to target by artillery or French defensive fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The sheer number of soldiers available made encirclement *en masse* and destruction of French formations relatively easy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The army was equipped with the Dreyse needle gun renowned for its use at the Battle of Königgrätz, which was by this time showing the age of its 25-year-old design.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The rifle had a range of only 600 m (2,000 ft) and lacked the rubber breech seal that permitted aimed shots.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The deficiencies of the needle gun were more than compensated for by the famous Krupp 6-pounder steel breech-loading cannons being issued to Prussian artillery batteries.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Firing a contact-detonated shell, the Krupp gun had a longer range and a higher rate of fire than the French bronze muzzle loading cannon, which relied on time fuses.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Prussian army was controlled by the General Staff, under General Helmuth von Moltke.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Prussian army was unique in Europe for having the only such organisation in existence, whose purpose in peacetime was to prepare the overall war strategy, and in wartime to direct operational movement and organise logistics and communications.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The officers of the General Staff were hand-picked from the Prussian *Kriegsakademie* (War Academy).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Moltke embraced new technology, particularly the railroad and telegraph, to coordinate and accelerate mobilisation of large forces.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 28 July 1870 Napoleon III left Paris for Metz and assumed command of the newly titled Army of the Rhine, some 202,448 strong and expected to grow as the French mobilization progressed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Marshal MacMahon took command of I Corps (4 infantry divisions) near Wissembourg; Marshal François Canrobert brought VI Corps (4 infantry divisions) to Châlons-sur-Marne in northern France as a reserve and to guard against a Prussian advance through Belgium.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A pre-war plan laid down by the late Marshal Niel called for a strong French offensive from Thionville towards Trier and into the Prussian Rhineland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This plan was discarded in favour of a defensive plan by Generals Charles Frossard and Bartélemy Lebrun, which called for the Army of the Rhine to remain in a defensive posture near the German border and repel any Prussian offensive.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] As Austria, along with Bavaria, Württemberg, and Baden were expected to join in a revenge war against Prussia, I Corps would invade the Bavarian Palatinate and proceed to "free" the four South German states in concert with Austro-Hungarian forces.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] VI Corps would reinforce either army as needed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Unfortunately for Frossard's plan, the Prussian army mobilised far more rapidly than expected.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Austro-Hungarians, still reeling after their defeat by Prussia in the Austro-Prussian War, were treading carefully before stating that they would only side with France if the south Germans viewed the French positively.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This did not materialize as the four South German states had come to Prussia's aid and were mobilizing their armies against France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon III was under substantial domestic pressure to launch an offensive before the full might of Moltke's forces was mobilized and deployed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Reconnaissance by Frossard's forces had identified only the Prussian 16th Infantry Division guarding the border town of Saarbrücken, right before the entire Army of the Rhine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Accordingly, on 31 July the Army marched forward toward the Saar River to seize Saarbrücken.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] General Frossard's II Corps and Marshal Bazaine's III Corps crossed the German border on 2 August, and began to force the Prussian 40th Regiment of the 16th Infantry Division from the town of Saarbrücken with a series of direct attacks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Chassepot rifle proved its worth against the Dreyse rifle, with French riflemen regularly outdistancing their Prussian counterparts in the skirmishing around Saarbrücken.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] However the Prussians resisted strongly, and the French suffered 86 casualties to the Prussian 83 casualties.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Saarbrücken also proved to be a major obstacle in terms of logistics.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Only one railway there led to the German hinterland but could be easily defended by a single force, and the only river systems in the region ran along the border instead of inland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Upon learning from captured Prussian soldiers and a local area police chief that the Prussian Crown Prince's Third Army was just 30 miles (48 km) north from Saarbrücken near the Rhine river town Wissembourg, General Le Bœuf and Napoleon III decided to retreat to defensive positions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] General Frossard, without instructions, hastily withdrew his elements of the Army of the Rhine in Saarbrücken back across the river to Spicheren and Forbach.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Marshal MacMahon, now closest to Wissembourg, spread his four divisions 20 miles (32 km) to react to any Prussian-Bavarian invasion.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This organization was due to a lack of supplies, forcing each division to seek out food and forage from the countryside and from the representatives of the army supply arm that was supposed to furnish them with provisions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] What made a bad situation much worse was the conduct of General Auguste-Alexandre Ducrot, commander of the 1st Division.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] He told General Abel Douay, commander of the 2nd Division, on 1 August that *"The information I have received makes me suppose that the enemy has no considerable forces very near his advance posts, and has no desire to take the offensive"*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Two days later, he told MacMahon that he had not found *"a single enemy post ... it looks to me as if the menace of the Bavarians is simply bluff"*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Even though Ducrot shrugged off the possibility of an attack by the Germans, MacMahon tried to warn his other three division commanders, without success.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The first action of the Franco-Prussian War took place on 4 August 1870.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This battle saw the unsupported division of General Douay of I Corps, with some attached cavalry, which was posted to watch the border, attacked in overwhelming but uncoordinated fashion by the German 3rd Army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] During the day, elements of a Bavarian and two Prussian corps became engaged and were aided by Prussian artillery, which blasted holes in the city defenses.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Douay held a very strong position initially, thanks to the accurate long-range rapid fire of the Chassepot rifles, but his force was too thinly stretched to hold it.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Douay was killed in the late morning when a caisson of the divisional mitrailleuse battery exploded near him; the encirclement of the town by the Prussians then threatened the French avenue of retreat.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The fighting within the town had become extremely intense, becoming a door to door battle of survival.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Despite an unceasing attack from Prussian infantry, the soldiers of the 2nd Division kept to their positions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The people of the town of Wissembourg finally surrendered to the Germans.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French troops who did not surrender retreated westward, leaving behind 1,000 dead and wounded and another 1,000 prisoners and all of their remaining ammunition.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The final attack by the Prussian troops also cost c.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German cavalry then failed to pursue the French and lost touch with them.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The attackers had an initial superiority of numbers, a broad deployment which made envelopment highly likely but the effectiveness of French Chassepot-rifle fire inflicted costly repulses on infantry attacks, until the French infantry had been extensively bombarded by the Prussian artillery.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Battle of Spicheren on 5 August was the second of three critical French defeats.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Moltke had originally planned to keep Bazaine's army on the Saar River until he could attack it with the 2nd Army in front and the 1st Army on its left flank, while the 3rd Army closed towards the rear.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The aging General von Steinmetz made an overzealous, unplanned move, leading the 1st Army south from his position on the Moselle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] He moved straight toward the town of Spicheren, cutting off Prince Frederick Charles from his forward cavalry units in the process.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On the French side, planning after the disaster at Wissembourg had become essential.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] General Le Bœuf, flushed with anger, was intent upon going on the offensive over the Saar and countering their loss.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] However, planning for the next encounter was more based upon the reality of unfolding events rather than emotion or pride, as Intendant General Wolff told him and his staff that supply beyond the Saar would be impossible.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Therefore, the armies of France would take up a defensive position that would protect against every possible attack point, but also left the armies unable to support each other.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] While the French army under General MacMahon engaged the German 3rd Army at the Battle of Wörth, the German 1st Army under Steinmetz finished their advance west from Saarbrücken.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A patrol from the German 2nd Army under Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia spotted decoy fires nearby and Frossard's army farther off on a distant plateau south of the town of Spicheren, and took this as a sign of Frossard's retreat.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Ignoring Moltke's plan again, both German armies attacked Frossard's French 2nd Corps, fortified between Spicheren and Forbach.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French were unaware of German numerical superiority at the beginning of the battle as the German 2nd Army did not attack all at once.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Treating the oncoming attacks as merely skirmishes, Frossard did not request additional support from other units.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] By the time he realized what kind of a force he was opposing, it was too late.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Seriously flawed communications between Frossard and those in reserve under Bazaine slowed down so much that by the time the reserves received orders to move out to Spicheren, German soldiers from the 1st and 2nd armies had charged up the heights.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Because the reserves had not arrived, Frossard erroneously believed that he was in grave danger of being outflanked, as German soldiers under General von Glume were spotted in Forbach.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Instead of continuing to defend the heights, by the close of battle after dusk he retreated to the south.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German casualties were relatively high due to the advance and the effectiveness of the Chassepot rifle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] They were quite startled in the morning when they had found out that their efforts were not in vain—Frossard had abandoned his position on the heights.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Battle of Wörth began when the two armies clashed again on 6 August near Wörth in the town of Frœschwiller, about 10 miles (16 km) from Wissembourg.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Crown Prince of Prussia's 3rd army had, on the quick reaction of his Chief of Staff General von Blumenthal, drawn reinforcements which brought its strength up to 140,000 troops.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French had been slowly reinforced and their force numbered only 35,000.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Although badly outnumbered, the French defended their position just outside Frœschwiller.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] By afternoon, the Germans had suffered c.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] 10,500 killed or wounded and the French had lost a similar number of casualties and another c.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] 9,200 men taken prisoner, a loss of about 50%.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Germans captured Fröschwiller which sat on a hilltop in the centre of the French line.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Having lost any hope for victory and facing a massacre, the French army disengaged and retreated in a westerly direction towards Bitche and Saverne, hoping to join French forces on the other side of the Vosges mountains.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German 3rd army did not pursue the French but remained in Alsace and moved slowly south, attacking and destroying the French garrisons in the vicinity.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] About 160,000 French soldiers were besieged in the fortress of Metz following the defeats on the frontier.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A retirement from Metz to link up with French forces at Châlons was ordered on 15 August and spotted by a Prussian cavalry patrol under Major Oskar von Blumenthal.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Next day a grossly outnumbered Prussian force of 30,000 men of III Corps (of the 2nd Army) under General Constantin von Alvensleben, found the French Army near Vionville, east of Mars-la-Tour.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Despite odds of four to one, the III Corps launched a risky attack.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French were routed and the III Corps captured Vionville, blocking any further escape attempts to the west.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Once blocked from retreat, the French in the fortress of Metz had no choice but to engage in a fight that would see the last major cavalry engagement in Western Europe.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The battle soon erupted, and III Corps was shattered by incessant cavalry charges, losing over half its soldiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German Official History recorded 15,780 casualties and French casualties of 13,761 men.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 16 August, the French had a chance to sweep away the key Prussian defense, and to escape.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Two Prussian corps had attacked the French advance guard, thinking that it was the rearguard of the retreat of the French Army of the Meuse.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Despite this misjudgment the two Prussian corps held the entire French army for the whole day.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Outnumbered 5 to 1, the extraordinary élan of the Prussians prevailed over gross indecision by the French.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French had lost the opportunity to win a decisive victory.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Battle of Gravelotte, or Gravelotte–St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Privat (18 August), was the largest battle in the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] It was fought about 6 miles (9.7 km) west of Metz, where on the previous day, having intercepted the French army's retreat to the west at the Battle of Mars-La-Tour, the Prussians were now closing in to complete the destruction of the French forces.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The combined German forces, under Field Marshal Count Helmuth von Moltke, were the Prussian First and Second Armies of the North German Confederation numbering about 210 infantry battalions, 133 cavalry squadrons, and 732 artillery pieces totaling 188,332 officers and men.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 18 August, the battle began when at 08:00 Moltke ordered the First and Second Armies to advance against the French positions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French were dug in with trenches and rifle pits with their artillery and their mitrailleuses in concealed positions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Backed by artillery fire, Steinmetz's VII and VIII Corps launched attacks across the Mance ravine, all of which were defeated by French rifle and mitrailleuse firepower, forcing the two German corps' to withdraw to Rezonville.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Prussian 1st Guards Infantry Division assaulted French-held St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Privat and was pinned down by French fire from rifle pits and trenches.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Second Army under Prince Frederick Charles used its artillery to pulverize the French position at St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] His XII Corps took the town of Roncourt and helped the Guard conquer St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Privat, while Eduard von Fransecky's II Corps advanced across the Mance ravine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The next morning the French Army of the Rhine retreated to Metz where they were besieged and forced to surrender two months later.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] A grand total of 20,163 German troops were killed, wounded or missing in action during the August 18 battle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French losses were 7,855 killed and wounded along with 4,420 prisoners of war (half of them were wounded) for a total of 12,275.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With the defeat of Marshal Bazaine's Army of the Rhine at Gravelotte, the French retreated to Metz, where they were besieged by over 150,000 Prussian troops of the First and Second Armies.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Further military operations on the part of the army under Bazaine's command have drawn numerous criticisms from historians against its commander.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] It was later stated with derogatory irony that his occupation at that time was writing orders on hygiene and discipline, as well as playing dominoes.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bazaine's surprising inactivity was a great relief to Moltke, who now had time to improve his lines around Metz and intensify the hunt for MacMahon.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] At this time, Napoleon III and MacMahon formed the new French Army of Châlons to march on to Metz to rescue Bazaine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon III personally led the army with Marshal MacMahon in attendance.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Army of Châlons marched northeast towards the Belgian border to avoid the Prussians before striking south to link up with Bazaine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Prussians took advantage of this maneuver to catch the French in a pincer grip.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Moltke left the Prussian First and Second Armies besieging Metz, except three corps detached to form the Army of the Meuse under the Crown Prince of Saxony.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With this army and the Prussian Third Army, Moltke marched northward and caught up with the French at Beaumont on 30 August.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] After a sharp fight in which they lost 5,000 men and 40 cannons, the French withdrew toward Sedan.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Having reformed in the town, the Army of Châlons was immediately isolated by the converging Prussian armies.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Napoleon III ordered the army to break out of the encirclement immediately.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With MacMahon wounded on the previous day, General Auguste Ducrot took command of the French troops in the field.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] On 1 September 1870, the battle opened with the Army of Châlons, with 202 infantry battalions, 80 cavalry squadrons and 564 guns, attacking the surrounding Prussian Third and Meuse Armies totaling 222 infantry battalions, 186 cavalry squadrons and 774 guns.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] General Emmanuel Félix de Wimpffen, the commander of the French V Corps in reserve, hoped to launch a combined infantry and cavalry attack against the Prussian XI Corps.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] But by 11:00, Prussian artillery took a toll on the French while more Prussian troops arrived on the battlefield.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The struggle in the conditions of encirclement turned out to be absolutely impossible for the French—their front was shot through with artillery fire from three sides.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French cavalry, commanded by General Margueritte, launched three desperate attacks on the nearby village of Floing where the Prussian XI Corps was concentrated.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Margueritte was mortally wounded leading the very first charge, dying 4 days later, and the two additional charges led to nothing but heavy losses.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] By the end of the day, with no hope of breaking out, Napoleon III called off the attacks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French lost over 17,000 men, killed or wounded, with 21,000 captured.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The Prussians reported their losses at 2,320 killed, 5,980 wounded and 700 captured or missing.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] By the next day, on 2 September, Napoleon III surrendered and was taken prisoner with 104,000 of his soldiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] It was an overwhelming victory for the Prussians, who had captured an entire French army and the leader of France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] They subsequently paraded the defeated French army in view of the besieged army in Metz, which had an impact on the morale of the defenders.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The defeat of the French at Sedan had decided the war in Prussia's favour.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] One French army was now immobilised and besieged in the city of Metz, and nothing was preventing a Prussian invasion.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] This defeat was humiliating for the already morally defeated French army and paved the way for the Siege of Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bazaine, a well-known Bonapartist, at this time allowed himself to be carried away by illusory plans for a political role in France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Even ignoring moral issues and potential public outcry, this plan seems completely unrealistic.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bismarck and Moltke answered Bazaine's offer of "cooperation" against the "republican menace" with an indifferent shrug.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The German press, undoubtedly at the instigation of Bismarck, widely covered this topic, and reported the details of Bazaine's negotiations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] The French press could only remain completely silent on this issue.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] With whom Bazaine negotiated still raises questions among historians.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] "For a decade, the French were considered him (M.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Edmond Regnier) a sinister figure, almost certainly an agent of Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] They would have been more justified in thinking him a buffoon".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Undoubtedly, the politically motivated actions of Commander Bazaine led to the passivity of the encircled army at Metz and contributed to the defeat of not only this army, but the country as a whole.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] Bazaine's army surrendered on 26 October.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] 173,000 people surrendered, with the Prussians capturing the huge amount of military equipment located in Metz.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p01] After the war, Marshal Bazaine was convicted by a French military court.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] When news of Napoleon III's surrender at Sedan arrived in Paris, the Second Empire was overthrown by a popular uprising.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 4 September, Jules Favre, Léon Gambetta, and General Louis-Jules Trochu proclaimed a provisional government called the Government of National Defence and a Third Republic.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the German victory at Sedan, most of the French standing army was either besieged in Metz or held prisoner by the Germans, who hoped for an armistice and an end to the war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck wanted an early peace but had difficulty finding a legitimate French authority with whom to negotiate.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Emperor was a captive and the Empress in exile, but there had been no abdication *de jure* and the army was still bound by an oath of allegiance to the defunct imperial regime; on the other hand, the Government of National Defence had no electoral mandate.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Prussia's intention was to weaken the political position of France abroad.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The defensive position of the new French authorities, who offered Germany an honorable peace and reimbursement of the costs of the war, was presented by Prussia as aggressive; they rejected the conditions put forward and demanded the annexation of the French provinces of Alsace and part of Lorraine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck was dangling the Emperor over the republic's head, calling Napoleon III "the legitimate ruler of France" and dismissing Gambetta's new republic as no more than "*un coup de parti*" ("a partisan coup").
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This policy was to some extent successful; the European press discussed the legitimacy of the French authorities, and Prussia's aggressive position was to some extent understood.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Only the United States and Spain recognized the Government of National Defence immediately after the announcement; other countries refused to do this for some time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The question of legitimacy is rather strange for France after the coup d'état of 1851, since Louis-Napoleon himself only overthrew the Second Republic and rose to the imperial throne by means of a coup d'état.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans expected to negotiate an end to the war, but while the republican government was amenable to war reparations or ceding colonial territories in Africa or Southeast Asia, it would go no further.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On behalf of the Government of National Defense, Favre declared on 6 September that France would not "yield an inch of its territory nor a stone of its fortresses".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The republic then renewed the declaration of war, called for recruits in all parts of the country, and pledged to drive the German troops out of France by a *guerre à outrance* ('overwhelming attack').
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans continued the war, yet could not pin down any proper military opposition in their vicinity.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] As the bulk of the remaining French armies was digging in near Paris, the German leaders decided to put pressure upon their enemy by attacking there.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] By 15 September, German troops had reached the outskirts and Moltke issued the orders to surround the city.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 19 September, the Germans surrounded it and erected a blockade, as already established at Metz, completing the encirclement on 20 September.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck met Favre on 18 September at the Château de Ferrières and demanded a frontier immune to a French war of revenge, which included Strasbourg, Alsace, and most of the Moselle department in Lorraine, of which Metz was the capital.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In return for an armistice for the French to elect a National Assembly, Bismarck demanded the surrender of Strasbourg and the fortress city of Toul.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] To allow supplies into Paris, one of the perimeter forts had to be handed over.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Favre was unaware that Bismarck's real aim in making such extortionate demands was to establish a durable peace on Germany's new western frontier, preferably by a peace with a friendly government, on terms acceptable to French public opinion.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] An impregnable military frontier was an inferior alternative to him, favoured only by the militant nationalists on the German side.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] When the war had begun, European public opinion heavily favoured the Germans; many Italians attempted to sign up as volunteers at the Prussian embassy in Florence and a Prussian diplomat visited Giuseppe Garibaldi in Caprera.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Today I say to you: rescue the French Republic by every means." Garibaldi went to France and assumed command of the Army of the Vosges, with which he operated around Dijon until the end of the war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The energetic actions of a part of the government (delegation) in Tours under Gambetta's leadership led to significant success in the formation of a new army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In less than four months, with persistent battles at the front, eleven new corps were formed (Nos.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The average success of the formation was equal to six thousand infantrymen and two batteries per day.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This success was achieved despite the fact that the military industry and warehouses were concentrated mainly in Paris; all supplies in the province—chiefs, weapons, camps, uniforms, ammunition, equipment, baggage—had to be improvised anew.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Many branches of the military industry were re-established in the province.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Freedom of communication with foreign markets brought significant benefits; it was possible to make large purchases on foreign markets, mainly English, Belgian, and American.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The artillery created by Gambetta in four months—238 batteries—was one and a half times larger than the artillery of imperial France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In the end, eight corps participated in the battles, and three were ready only by the end of January, when a truce was already concluded.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] While the Germans had a 2:1 numerical advantage before Napoleon III's surrender, this French recruitment gave them a 2:1 or 3:1 advantage.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Prussia was completely unaware of the feverish activity of permanent mobilization.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This disparity in forces created a crisis for the Germans at the front in November 1870, which only the release of the large forces besieging the fortress of Metz allowed them to overcome.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Prussian forces commenced the siege of Paris on 19 September 1870.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Faced with the blockade, the new French government called for the establishment of several large armies in the French provinces.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] These new bodies of troops were to march towards Paris and attack the Germans there from various directions at the same time.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Armed French civilians were to create a guerilla force—the so-called *Francs-tireurs*—for the purpose of attacking German supply lines.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck was an active supporter of the bombardment of the city.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] He sought to end the war as soon as possible, very much fearing a change in the international situation unfavorable to Prussia, as he himself called it "the intervention of neutrals".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Therefore, Bismarck constantly and actively insisted on the early start of the bombardment, despite all the objections of the military command.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Von Blumenthal, who commanded the siege, was opposed to the bombardment on moral grounds.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In this he was backed by other senior military figures such as the Crown Prince and Moltke.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Nevertheless, in January, the Germans fired some 12,000 shells (300–400 daily) into the city.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The siege of the city caused great hardships for the population, especially for the poor from cold and hunger.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Dispatched from Paris as the republican government emissary, Léon Gambetta flew over the German lines in a balloon inflated with coal gas from the city's gasworks and organized the recruitment of the Armée de la Loire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Rumors about an alleged German "extermination" plan infuriated the French and strengthened their support of the new regime.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Within a few weeks, five new armies totalling more than 500,000 troops were recruited.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans dispatched some of their troops to the French provinces to detect, attack and disperse the new French armies before they could become a menace.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans were not prepared for an occupation of the whole of France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 10 October, hostilities began between German and French republican forces near Orléans.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] At first, the Germans were victorious but the French drew reinforcements and defeated a Bavarian force at the Battle of Coulmiers on 9 November.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the surrender of Metz, more than 100,000 well-trained and experienced German troops joined the German 'Southern Army'.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French were forced to abandon Orléans on 4 December, and were finally defeated at the Battle of Le Mans (10–12 January).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] A second French army which operated north of Paris was turned back at the Battle of Amiens (27 November), the Battle of Bapaume (3 January 1871) and the Battle of St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Following the Army of the Loire's defeats, Gambetta turned to General Faidherbe's Army of the North.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The army had achieved several small victories at towns such as Ham, La Hallue, and Amiens and was protected by the belt of fortresses in northern France, allowing Faidherbe's men to launch quick attacks against isolated Prussian units, then retreat behind the fortresses.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Despite access to the armaments factories of Lille, the Army of the North suffered from severe supply difficulties, which depressed morale.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In January 1871, Gambetta forced Faidherbe to march his army beyond the fortresses and engage the Prussians in open battle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The army was severely weakened by low morale, supply problems, the terrible winter weather and low troop quality, whilst general Faidherbe was unable to command due to his poor health, the result of decades of campaigning in West Africa.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Quentin, the Army of the North suffered a crushing defeat and was scattered, releasing thousands of Prussian soldiers to be relocated to the East.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Following the destruction of the French Army of the Loire, remnants of the Loire army gathered in eastern France to form the Army of the East, commanded by general Charles-Denis Bourbaki.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In a final attempt to cut the German supply lines in northeast France, Bourbaki's army marched north to attack the Prussian siege of Belfort and relieve the defenders.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French troops had a significant advantage (110 thousand soldiers against 40 thousand).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French offensive took the Germans by surprise and by mid-January 1871, the French had reached the Lisaine River, just a few kilometers from the besieged fortress of Belfort.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In the battle of the Lisaine, Bourbaki's men failed to break through German lines commanded by General August von Werder.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bringing in the German 'Southern Army', General von Manteuffel then drove Bourbaki's army into the mountains near the Swiss border.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bourbaki attempted to commit suicide, though survived his wound.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Facing annihilation, the last intact French army of 87,000 men (now commanded by General Justin Clinchant) crossed the border and was disarmed and interned by the neutral Swiss near Pontarlier (1 February).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The besieged fortress of Belfort continued to resist until the signing of the armistice, repelling a German attempt to capture the fortress on 27 January, which was some consolation for the French in this stubborn and unhappy campaign.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 26 January 1871, the Government of National Defence based in Paris negotiated an armistice with the Prussians.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] With Paris starving, and Gambetta's provincial armies reeling from one disaster after another, French foreign minister Favre went to Versailles on 24 January to discuss peace terms with Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck agreed to end the siege and allow food convoys to immediately enter Paris (including trains carrying millions of German army rations), on condition that the Government of National Defence surrender several key fortresses outside Paris to the Prussians.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Without the forts, the French Army would no longer be able to defend Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Although public opinion in Paris was strongly against any form of surrender or concession to the Prussians, the Government realised that it could not hold the city for much longer, and that Gambetta's provincial armies would probably never break through to relieve Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] President Trochu resigned on 25 January and was replaced by Favre, who signed the surrender two days later at Versailles, with the armistice coming into effect at midnight.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 28 January, a truce was concluded for 21 days, after the exhaustion of food and fuel supplies, the Paris garrison capitulated, the National Guard retained its weapons, while German troops occupied part of the forts of Paris to prevent the possibility of resuming hostilities.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] But military operations continued in the eastern part of the country, in the area of operation of the Bourbaki army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French side, having no reliable information about the outcome of the struggle, insisted on excluding this area from the truce in the hope of a successful outcome of the struggle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans did not dissuade the French.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Several sources claim that in his carriage on the way back to Paris, Favre broke into tears, and collapsed into his daughter's arms as the guns around Paris fell silent at midnight.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] At Bordeaux, Gambetta received word from Paris on 29 January that the Government had surrendered.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Jules Simon, a member of the Government arrived from Paris by train on 1 February to negotiate with Gambetta.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Another group of three ministers arrived in Bordeaux on 5 February and the following day Gambetta stepped down and surrendered control of the provincial armies to the Government of National Defence, which promptly ordered a cease-fire across France.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] When the war began, the French government ordered a blockade of the North German coasts, which the small North German Federal Navy with only five ironclads and various minor vessels could do little to oppose.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] For most of the war, the three largest German ironclads were out of service with engine troubles; only the turret ship SMS *Arminius* was available to conduct operations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] By the time engine repairs had been completed, the French fleet had already departed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The blockade proved only partially successful due to crucial oversights by the planners in Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Reservists that were supposed to be at the ready in case of war, were working in the Newfoundland fisheries or in Scotland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Only part of the 470-ship French Navy put to sea on 24 July.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Before long, the French navy ran short of coal, needing 200 short tons (180 t) per day and having a bunker capacity in the fleet of only 250 short tons (230 t).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] A blockade of Wilhelmshaven failed, and conflicting orders about operations in the Baltic Sea or a return to France made the French naval efforts futile.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Spotting a blockade-runner became unwelcome because of the *question du charbon*; pursuit of Prussian ships quickly depleted the coal reserves of the French ships.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] But the main reason for the only partial success of the naval operation was the fear of the French command to risk political complications with Great Britain.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This deterred the French command from trying to interrupt German trade under the British flag.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Despite the limited measures of the blockade, it still created noticeable difficulties for German trade.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] "The actual captures of German ships were eighty in number".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] To relieve pressure from the expected German attack into Alsace-Lorraine, Napoleon III and the French high command planned a seaborne invasion of northern Germany as soon as war began.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French expected the invasion to divert German troops and to encourage Denmark to join in the war, with its 50,000-strong army and the Royal Danish Navy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] They discovered that Prussia had recently built defences around the big North German ports, including coastal artillery batteries with Krupp heavy artillery, which with a range of 4,000 yards (3,700 m), had double the range of French naval guns.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French Navy lacked the heavy guns to engage the coastal defences and the topography of the Prussian coast made a seaborne invasion of northern Germany impossible.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French Marines intended for the invasion of northern Germany were dispatched to reinforce the French Army of Châlons and fell into captivity at Sedan along with Napoleon III.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] A shortage of officers, following the capture of most of the professional French army at the siege of Metz and at the Battle of Sedan, led to naval officers being sent from their ships to command hastily assembled reservists of the *Garde Mobile*.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] As the autumn storms of the North Sea forced the return of more of the French ships, the blockade of the north German ports diminished and in September 1870 the French navy abandoned the blockade for the winter.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The rest of the navy retired to ports along the English Channel and remained in port for the rest of the war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Outside Europe, the French corvette *Dupleix* blockaded the German corvette SMS *Hertha* in Nagasaki and the Battle of Havana took place between the Prussian gunboat SMS *Meteor* and the French aviso *Bouvet* off Havana, Cuba, in November 1870.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Franco-Prussian War of 1870–71 resulted in numerous war crimes committed by the Prussian army.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] One notable war crime committed during the conflict was the execution of prisoners of war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Reports indicate that several hundred French prisoners were summarily executed by Prussian soldiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This included the execution of a group of over 200 French soldiers at the village of Dornach, which was subsequently referred to as the "Dornach atrocities".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In the small town of Bazeilles, near Sedan, French marines and partisans put up a resistance against a force of Bavarian soldiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the initial French resistance was overcome, the Bavarian troops shelled the village with artillery before sending in infantry to continue the assault.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In battle, some surrendering soldiers were shot on the spot, and over 400 buildings were destroyed.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Bavarian troops detained around one hundred civilians, believing they illegally took part in the battle, only to release them unharmed the next day.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the war investigations established that 39 civilians were killed or wounded during the battle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Prussian soldiers were also accused of committing acts of violence against civilians, including murder, rape, and the destruction of property.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The quick German victory over the French stunned neutral observers, many of whom had expected a French victory and a long war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The strategic advantages the Germans had were not appreciated outside Germany until after hostilities had ceased.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Other countries quickly discerned the advantages given to the Germans by their military system, and adopted many of their innovations, particularly the general staff, universal conscription, and highly detailed mobilization systems.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian General Staff developed by Moltke proved to be extremely effective, in contrast to the traditional French school.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This was in large part because the Prussian General Staff was created to study previous Prussian operations and learn to avoid mistakes.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The structure also greatly strengthened Moltke's ability to control large formations spread out over significant distances.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Chief of the General Staff, effectively the commander in chief of the Prussian army, was independent of the minister of war and answered only to the monarch.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French General Staff—along with those of every other European military—was little better than a collection of assistants for the line commanders.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This disorganization hampered the French commanders' ability to exercise control of their forces.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In addition, the Prussian military education system was superior to the French model; Prussian staff officers were trained to exhibit initiative and independent thinking.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French, meanwhile, suffered from an education and promotion system that stifled intellectual development.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Albrecht von Roon, the Prussian Minister of War from 1859 to 1873, put into effect a series of reforms of the Prussian military system in the 1860s.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Among these were two major reforms that substantially increased the military power of Germany.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The first was a reorganization of the army that integrated the regular army and the *Landwehr* reserves.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The second was the provision for the conscription of every male Prussian of military age in the event of mobilization.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Thus, although the population of France was greater than the population of all of the Northern German states that participated in the war, the Germans mobilized more soldiers for battle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] At the start of the Franco-Prussian War, 462,000 German soldiers concentrated on the French frontier while only 270,000 French soldiers could be moved to face them, the French army having lost 100,000 stragglers before a shot was fired, through poor planning and administration.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This was partly due to the peacetime organisations of the armies.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Each Prussian Corps was based within a *Kreis* (literally "circle") around the chief city in an area.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Reservists rarely lived more than a day's travel from their regiment's depot.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] By contrast, French regiments generally served far from their depots, which in turn were not in the areas of France from which their soldiers were drawn.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Reservists often faced several days' journey to report to their depots, and then another long journey to join their regiments.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Large numbers of reservists choked railway stations, vainly seeking rations and orders.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The effect of these differences was accentuated by the peacetime preparations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian General Staff had drawn up minutely detailed mobilization plans using the railway system, which in turn had been partly laid out in response to recommendations of a Railway Section within the General Staff.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French railway system, with competing companies, had developed purely from commercial pressures and many journeys to the front in Alsace and Lorraine involved long diversions and frequent changes between trains.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] There was no system of military control of the railways and officers simply commandeered trains as they saw fit.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Rail sidings and marshalling yards became choked with loaded wagons, with nobody responsible for unloading them or directing them to the destination.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] France also suffered from an outdated tactical system.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Although referred to as "Napoleonic tactics", this system was developed by Antoine-Henri Jomini during his time in Russia.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Surrounded by a rigid aristocracy with a "Sacred Social Order" mentality, Jomini's system was equally rigid and inflexible.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] His system simplified several formations that were meant for an entire army, using battalions as the building blocks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] His system was simple, but only strong enough to attack in one direction.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The system was adopted by the Bourbons to prevent a repeat of when Napoleon I had returned to France, and Napoleon III retained the system upon his ascension to power (hence why they became associated with his family name).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussians in contrast did not use battalions as their basic tactical unit, and their system was much more flexible.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Companies were formed into columns and attacked in parallel, rather than as a homogeneous battalion-sized block.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Attacking in parallel allowed each company to choose its own axis of advance and make the most of local cover.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] It also permitted the Prussians to fire at oblique angles, raking the French lines with rifle fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Thus, even though the Prussians had inferior rifles, they still inflicted more casualties with rifle fire than the French, with 53,900 French killed by the Dreyse (70% of their war casualties) versus 25,475 Germans killed by the Chassepot (96% of their war casualties).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Although Austria-Hungary and Denmark had both wished to avenge their recent military defeats against Prussia, they chose not to intervene in the war due to a lack of confidence in the French.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] These countries did not have a documented alliance with France, and they were too late to start a war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the rapid and stunning victories of Prussia, they preferred to abandon any plans to intervene in the war altogether.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Napoleon III also failed to cultivate alliances with the Russian Empire and the United Kingdom, partially due to the diplomatic efforts of the Prussian chancellor Otto von Bismarck.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck had bought Tsar Alexander II's complicity by promising to help restore his naval access to the Black Sea and Mediterranean (cut off by the treaties ending the Crimean War), other powers were less biddable.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] "Seizing upon the distraction of the Franco-Prussian War, Russia in November 1870 had begun rebuilding its naval bases in the Black Sea, a clear violation of the treaty that had ended the Crimean War fourteen years earlier".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the peace of Frankfurt in 1871, a rapprochement between France and Russia was born.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] "Instead of forging ties with Russia in the east and further crippling France in the west, Bismarck's miscalculation had opened the door to future relations between Paris and St.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The culmination of this new relationship will finally be the Franco-Russian Alliance of 1894; an alliance that explicitly refers to the perceived threat of Germany and its military response".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Britain did not oppose Prussia's strengthened position in Europe as it viewed France as its traditional rival in international affairs.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The British statesman Lord Palmerston wrote in 1865: "The current Prussia is too weak to be honest and independent in its actions.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] And, taking into account the interests of the future, it is highly desirable for Germany as a whole became strong, so she was able to keep the ambitious and warlike nation, France, and Russia, which compress it from the West and the East".
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The English historian William Baring Pemberton argued that Palmerston misunderstood Bismarck's policies and intentions due to his adherence to outdated ideas.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Over time, the British government began to understand that France's defeat had led to a radical change in the European balance of power.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The period following the war was marked by a decline in Anglo-German relations as the German Empire embarked on a process of colonial and naval expansion, which was received negatively in Britain.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the Peace of Prague in 1866, the nominally independent German states of Saxony, Bavaria, Württemberg, Baden and Hesse-Darmstadt (the southern part that was not included in the North German Union) remained.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] After the diplomatic provocation in Bad Ems, these states had no room for maneuver, the war was presented by Bismarck as a war for national independence against an external enemy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] All these states joined the Prussian war from the very beginning of hostilities.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In January 1871, these states became part of the German Empire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French breech-loading rifle, the Chassepot, had a longer range than the German needle gun; 1,400 metres (1,500 yd) compared to 550 m (600 yd).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French also had an early machine-gun type weapon, the mitrailleuse, which could fire its thirty-seven barrels at a range of around 1,100 m (1,200 yd).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] It was developed in such secrecy that little training with the weapon had occurred, leaving French gunners with little experience; the gun was treated like artillery and in this role it was ineffective.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Worse still, once the small number of soldiers who had been trained how to use the new weapon became casualties, there were no replacements who knew how to operate the mitrailleuse.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The French were equipped with bronze, rifled muzzle-loading artillery, while the Prussians used new steel breech-loading guns, which had a far longer range and a faster rate of fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Prussian gunners strove for a high rate of fire, which was discouraged in the French army in the belief that it wasted ammunition.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In addition, the Prussian artillery batteries had 30% more guns than their French counterparts (8 guns per Prussian battery compared to 6 French guns).
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian guns typically opened fire at a range of 2–3 kilometres (1.2–1.9 mi), beyond the range of French artillery or the Chassepot rifle.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian batteries could thus destroy French artillery with impunity, before being moved forward to directly support infantry attacks.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans fired 30,000,000 rounds of small arms ammunition and 362,662 field artillery rounds.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The events of the Franco-Prussian War had great influence on military thinking over the next forty years.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Lessons drawn from the war included the need for a general staff system, the scale and duration of future wars and the tactical use of artillery and cavalry.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The bold use of artillery by the Prussians, to silence French guns at long range and then to directly support infantry attacks at close range, proved to be superior to the defensive doctrine employed by French gunners.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Likewise, the war showed that breech-loading cannons were superior to muzzle-loaded cannons, just as the Austro-Prussian War of 1866 had demonstrated for rifles.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian tactics and designs were adopted by European armies by 1914, exemplified in the French 75, an artillery piece optimised to provide direct fire support to advancing infantry.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Most European armies ignored the evidence of the Russo-Japanese War of 1904–1905 which suggested that infantry armed with new smokeless-powder rifles could engage gun crews effectively in the open.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This forced gunners to fire at longer range using indirect fire, usually from a position of cover.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The heavy use of fortifications and dugouts in the Russo-Japanese war also greatly undermined the usefulness of field artillery which was not designed for indirect fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] At the Battle of Mars-La-Tour, the Prussian 12th Cavalry Brigade, commanded by General Adalbert von Bredow, conducted a charge against a French artillery battery.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The attack was a costly success and came to be known as "von Bredow's Death Ride", but which nevertheless was held to prove that cavalry charges could still prevail on the battlefield.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Use of traditional cavalry on the battlefields of 1914 proved to be disastrous, due to accurate, long-range rifle fire, machine-guns and artillery.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bredow's attack had succeeded only because of an unusually effective artillery bombardment just before the charge, along with favorable terrain that masked his approach.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] A third influence was the effect on notions of entrenchment and its limitations.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] While the American Civil War had famously involved entrenchment in the final years of the war, the Prussian system had overwhelmed French attempts to use similar tactics.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] With Prussian tactics seeming to make entrenchment and prolonged offensive campaigns ineffective, the experience of the American Civil War was seen as that of a musket war, not a rifle war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Many European armies were convinced of the viability of the "cult of the offensive" because of this, and focused their attention on aggressive bayonet charges over infantry fire.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] These would needlessly expose men to artillery fire in 1914, and entrenchment would return with a vengeance.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Germans deployed a total of 33,101 officers and 1,113,254 men into France, of whom they lost 1,046 officers and 16,539 enlisted men killed in action.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Another 671 officers and 10,050 men died of their wounds, for total battle deaths of 28,306.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Disease killed 207 officers and 11,940 men, with typhoid accounting for 6,965.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] 4,009 were missing and presumed dead; 290 died in accidents and 29 committed suicide.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Among the missing and captured were 103 officers and 10,026 men.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The wounded amounted to 3,725 officers and 86,007 men.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] French battle deaths were 77,000, of which 41,000 were killed in action and 36,000 died of wounds.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Total deaths were 138,871, with 136,540 being suffered by the army and 2,331 by the navy.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] French prisoners of war numbered 383,860.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In addition, 90,192 French soldiers were interned in Switzerland and 6,300 in Belgium.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] During the war the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) established an international tracing agency in Basel for prisoners of that war.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The holdings of the "Basel Agency" were later transferred to the ICRC headquarters in Geneva and integrated into the ICRC archives, where they are accessible today.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Prussian Army, under the terms of the armistice, held a brief victory parade in Paris on 1 March; the city was silent and draped with black and the Germans quickly withdrew.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Bismarck honoured the armistice, by allowing train loads of food into Paris and withdrawing Prussian forces to the east of the city, prior to a full withdrawal once France agreed to pay a five billion franc war indemnity.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The indemnity was proportioned, according to population, to be the exact equivalent to the indemnity imposed by Napoleon on Prussia in 1807.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] At the same time, Prussian forces were concentrated in the provinces of Alsace and Lorraine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] An exodus occurred from Paris as some 200,000 people, predominantly middle-class, went to the countryside.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] During the war, the Paris National Guard, particularly in the working-class neighbourhoods of Paris, had become highly politicised and units elected officers; many refused to wear uniforms or obey commands from the national government.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] National guard units tried to seize power in Paris on 31 October 1870 and 22 January 1871.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] On 18 March 1871, when the regular army tried to remove cannons from an artillery park on Montmartre, National Guard units resisted and killed two army generals.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The national government and regular army forces retreated to Versailles and a revolutionary government was proclaimed in Paris.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] A commune was elected, which was dominated by socialists, anarchists and revolutionaries.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The red flag replaced the French tricolour and a civil war began between the Commune and the regular army, which attacked and recaptured Paris from 21–28 May in the *Semaine Sanglante* ("bloody week").
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] During the fighting, the Communards killed around 500 people, including Georges Darboy, the Archbishop of Paris, and burned down many government buildings, including the Tuileries Palace and the Hotel de Ville.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Communards captured with weapons were routinely shot by the army and Government troops killed between 7,000 and 30,000 Communards, both during the fighting and in massacres of men, women, and children during and after the Commune.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] More recent histories, based on studies of the number buried in Paris cemeteries and in mass graves after the fall of the Commune, put the number killed at between 6,000 and 10,000.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Twenty-six courts were established to try more than 40,000 people who had been arrested, which took until 1875 and imposed 95 death sentences, of which 23 were inflicted.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Forced labour for life was imposed on 251 people, 1,160 people were transported to "a fortified place" and 3,417 people were transported .
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] About 20,000 Communards were held in prison hulks until released in 1872 and a great many Communards fled abroad to the United Kingdom, Switzerland, Belgium or the United States.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The survivors were amnestied by a bill introduced by Gambetta in 1880 and allowed to return.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] In 1830, the French army invaded and conquered the Beylik of Algiers.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Afterwards, France colonized the country, setting up its own administration over Algeria.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The withdrawal of a large proportion of the army stationed in French Algeria to serve in the Franco-Prussian War had weakened France's control of the territory, while reports of defeats undermined French prestige amongst the indigenous population.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The most serious native insurrection since the time of Emir Abdelkader was the 1871 Mokrani Revolt in the Kabylia, which spread through much of Algeria.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] By April 1871, 250 tribes had risen, or nearly a third of Algeria's population.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The creation of a unified German Empire (which excluded Austria) greatly disturbed the balance of power that had been created with the Congress of Vienna after the end of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Germany had established itself as a major power in continental Europe, boasting one of the most powerful and professional armies in the world.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Although the UK remained the dominant world power overall, British involvement in European affairs during the late 19th century was limited, owing to its focus on colonial empire-building, allowing Germany to exercise great influence over the European mainland.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Anglo-German straining of tensions was somewhat mitigated by several prominent relationships between the two powers, such as the Crown Prince's marriage with the daughter of Queen Victoria.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The defeat in the Franco-Prussian War led to the birth of Revanchism (literally, "revenge-ism") in France, characterised by a deep sense of bitterness, hatred and demand for revenge against Germany.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] This was particularly manifested in loose talk of another war with Germany in order to reclaim Alsace and Lorraine.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] It also led to the development of nationalist ideologies emphasising "the ideal of the guarded, self-referential nation schooled in the imperative of war", an ideology epitomised by figures such as General Georges Ernest Boulanger in the 1880s.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Paintings that emphasized the humiliation of the defeat became in high demand, such as those by Alphonse de Neuville.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Revanchism was not a major cause of war in 1914 because it faded after 1880.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Keiger says, "By the 1880s Franco-German relations were relatively good." The French public had very little interest in foreign affairs and elite French opinion was strongly opposed to war with its more powerful neighbor.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The elites were now calm and considered it a minor issue.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] The Alsace-Lorraine issue remained a minor theme after 1880, and Republicans and Socialists systematically downplayed the issue.
[src:franco-prussian-war/franco-prussian-war-p02] Return did not become a French war aim until after World War I began.
